pr_review_body:
@tomchristie I think this solution is neat. We are not making much of a sacrifice here, we are just expanding the functionality.

From a user's point of view, this is a huge improvement.

Maybe we can move the `_get_request_state` and `_set_request_state` to another module, as we had the talk about moving the Starlette specific extensions to `["extensions"]["starlette"][<extension>]`.

@gibsondan Could you take a look at these guys to see if they also need to be updated?

- [Testing against production using branch deployments guide](https://docs.dagster.io/guides/dagster/branch_deployments#step-2-configure-our-job-for-each-environment)
- [Cloud environment variables reference](https://docs.dagster.io/dagster-cloud/developing-testing/environment-variables#all-deployment-variables)

@alirezazolanvari Thanks for your efforts 💯 
Please take a look at my comments.
And also please add some tests for `area` method errors to `error_test.py`

@lobsiger thanks a lot for adding this feature, it is very nice results you get!
I have just started with the review, but maybe we can start with that?
There is a lot of places which are flagged as not tested indeed. I understand that Xarray can be a bit frightening, how about starting with tests using regular numpy arrays first, that we can then adapt to Xarray?

@cxznmhdcxz @zhoxing-ms
It seems we can not test `snapshot grant-access`.
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/18628534/149056467-65295e74-0ac2-4f81-8ec1-6d50fd16f5f3.png)

@nabokovas Thank you very much for this update! You've just done my job 🙂 

@jameslamb Let me kindly disagree with you. According to our policy, we try to use the most recent environments at Travis (https://github.com/microsoft/LightGBM/pull/3393#issue-486186591) and update them quite often. I remember, we even used betas.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25141164/97639748-3d1dc880-1a50-11eb-8fd4-ec207de3df4c.png)


I believe it's better to spot a compilation problem at our CI before users come and report it.
Moreover, we are speaking about macOS where it seems users tend to use the last available software in contrast to Linux where one have to use 10-years old CentOS distribution.

FYI, yesterday I tried to use Big Sur, but unfortunately without any luck due to dependency unavailability: #3499.

@withshubh , thanks, that's fantastic! Two things before merging:

1) Take a look at my comment on removing ``fastapi.Request`` import.
2) Target the PR to develop branch.

@pmeier Thanks for the work.

I agree with the direction of the PR. I have 2 concerns over the use of `copy` and the introduction of more methods in some of the `_Feature` subclasses.

Concerning the conflicts with other PRs, this PR looks like it adds more tests and aligns the API which is less dangerous than rewriting the `convert_dtype_image_tensor` method. How confident are you about the changes on the other PR? Do you think we can benefit by these extra tests and thus prioritise merging this PR first?

The tests and all the core logic makes sense. There are a few cases that I think might've been missed.

As @RobbieMcKinstry pointed out, the PropertyPath.reset implementation is a bit difficult to follow.
The comments help, but I'm wondering about how we can make this more maintainable.
I think one easy bit might be to branch on "leaf or not" first, and then on types, since the bulk of the code is in the leaf handling.

```go
if len(p) > 1 {
  // Not a leaf. Traverse.
  key, p := p[0], p[1:]
  switch key := key.(type) {
  // ...
  }
}

// Leaf. Reset matched values.
switch key := key.(type) {
// ...
}
```

Thank you for your proposal @carylee.

The annotations we'll need here are a little bit more subtle, as we have to capture dependency between inputs and outputs. 

```python
    @overload
    def approxQuantile(
        self,
        col: str,
        probabilities: Union[List[float], Tuple[float]],
        relativeError: float
    ) -> List[float]: ...
    @overload
    def approxQuantile(
        self,
        col: Union[List[str], Tuple[str]],
        probabilities: Union[List[float], Tuple[float]],
        relativeError: float
    ) -> List[List[float]]: ...
```

So if the input is a string, the output is a list of strings. Otherwise a list of lists of strings.
